        "text": "The document page is from the 2002 Annual Report by the Market Oversight Division of the Public Utility Commission of Texas. It discusses the costs and methods related to balancing energy and managing congestion in the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) market.\n\n### Key Points:\n\n1. **Balancing Energy Costs:**\n   - The table shows the total costs for balancing energy in 2001 and 2002. In 2001, the total cost was approximately $75.7 million, while in 2002, it increased to about $114.2 million.\n\n2. **Congestion Management Method:**\n   - ERCOT uses a zonal, portfolio-based model to manage congestion, identifying key interfaces as Commercially Significant Constraints (CSCs).\n   - In 2001, there were three zones and two CSCs; in 2002, there were four zones and four CSCs.\n   - Congestion is managed in two steps: dispatching zonal balancing energy and issuing specific instructions to resolve local congestion.\n   - If no zonal congestion exists, the Market Clearing Price for Energy (MCPE) is uniform across ERCOT.\n\n3. **Zonal Congestion Costs:**\n   - During the first 17 months, zonal congestion charges were $187.66 million, with a significant portion ($136.74 million) occurring in August 2001.\n   - New market rules introduced on February 15, 2002, required direct assignment of zonal congestion costs and introduced Transmission Congestion Rights (TCRs) for hedging.\n   - Zonal congestion charges from July 31, 2001, to February 15, 2002, were $165 million, with a reduction in charges from February 15 to December 2002.\n\nThe document provides insights into the financial and operational strategies employed by ERCOT to manage energy balancing and congestion, highlighting the changes and challenges faced during the specified period.",
