      },
      {
        "id": "678cbf77-3c6a-4e57-8b25-7a45bb52b88e",
        "score": 0.6167165,
        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 7 on Congestion Revenue Rights. It outlines definitions and payment protocols related to energy resources and settlements.\n\n1. **Definitions and Variables:**\n   - **RMR Resource:** Defined as the RMR contract price Energy Offer Curve at High Sustained Limit (HSL).\n   - **CLR and ESR:** New items to be implemented, with CLR equating to SWCAP and ESR set at $100/MWh.\n   - **MAXRESP and MAXRESPRK:** Maximum Resource Prices for sources and resources at specific settlement points.\n   - **r and k:** Represent a generation resource and a sink settlement point, respectively.\n\n2. **Payments for FGRs Settled in DAM:**\n   - Currently, there are no defined flowgates.\n\n3. **Payments and Charges for PTP Obligations with Refund Settled in DAM:**\n   - ERCOT will pay the owner of a PTP Obligation with Refund the difference in Day-Ahead Settlement Point Prices between the sink and source Settlement Points, subject to a refund charge if the price difference is positive.\n\nThe document includes placeholders for future system implementations and adjustments to definitions upon implementation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_7_-_Congestion_Revenue_Rights/page_56.jpg",
          "page_num": 56,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 7 - Congestion Revenue Rights",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d9cf18af-0dcf-4fee-a1b1-6cd143e5874a",
        "score": 0.6144721,
        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 9 on Settlement and Billing. It includes a table defining various variables related to settlement points, auctions, intervals, resources, and electrical buses. Key points include:\n\n1. **Allocation of Uplifted Short-Paid Amounts**: These amounts are distributed to Market Participants based on their pro-rata share of megawatt-hours (MWhs) contributed to a Counter-Party\u2019s activity ratio share.\n\n2. **Scheduling of Uplifted Amounts**: Any uplifted amount over $2,500,000 must be scheduled so that no single invoice exceeds this amount. ERCOT must issue these invoices at least 30 days apart.\n\n3. **Issuance of Default Uplift Invoices**: ERCOT will issue these invoices no earlier than 90 days after a short-pay of a Settlement Invoice. Recipients must access the invoice on the MIS Certified Area.\n\n4. **Contents of Default Uplift Invoices**: Each invoice must include the recipient's name, ERCOT identifier, net amount due, run date, invoice reference number, default uplift invoice reference, and payment date and time.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_67.jpg",
          "page_num": 67,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "358386a7-6785-401f-bf79-ddf1ef8de19c",
        "score": 0.60831434,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) regarding user fees and transmission billing determinants.\n\n1. **User Fees:**\n   - ERCOT is required to post user fees approved by the ERCOT Board on its website within two business days of any changes.\n   - Market Participants or other entities must pay these approved user fees.\n\n2. **Transmission Billing Determinant Calculation:**\n   - ERCOT provides Market Participants with necessary parameters and formulas to calculate billing charges for using Transmission or Distribution Facilities.\n   - ERCOT is not responsible for billing, collection, or disbursal of payments for transmission access service.\n\n3. **Billing Determinant Data Elements:**\n   - ERCOT calculates and provides data elements annually for Transmission Service Providers (TSPs) and Distribution Service Providers (DSPs) to use as billing determinants.\n   - Data must be provided by December 1 each year and comply with specific regulatory requirements.\n   - Key data elements include:\n     - The 4-Coincident Peak (4-CP) for each DSP and External Load Serving Entity (ELSE).\n     - The ERCOT average 4-CP.\n     - The average 4-CP for each DSP and ELSE coincident to the ERCOT average 4-CP.\n   - The ERCOT average 4-CP is the average of the coincidental MW peaks during June, July, August, and September.\n   - Coincidental MW peak is defined as the highest monthly Settlement Interval 15-minute MW peak for the entire ERCOT Transmission Grid, calculated using a specific formula involving net energy production and transfers.\n\nThe document also references updates to be made in accordance with NPRR995 and NPRR1188.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_52.jpg",
          "page_num": 52,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7bbaceba-7322-4069-a324-4ad5c6e53260",
        "score": 0.6075718,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 7: Congestion Revenue Rights of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025. It lists various energy sources and their associated costs or formulas for calculating costs in $/MWh. The sources include Hydro, Coal and Lignite, Combined Cycle, Gas-Steam Boilers, Simple Cycle, Diesel, Wind, Photovoltaic (PV), and Reliability Must-Run (RMR) Resources. Specific formulas involve the Fuel Index Price (FIP) and MMBtu/MWh multipliers for different types of energy generation. \n\nTwo placeholders, labeled NPRR1188 and NPRR1014, suggest future system implementations with specified costs for CLR and ESR. The page also defines variables MINRESPRi and MINRESPRPj, which represent the minimum resource prices for sources and resources at specific settlement points.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_7_-_Congestion_Revenue_Rights/page_54.jpg",
          "page_num": 54,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 7 - Congestion Revenue Rights",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1b6b9f97-40eb-4904-be64-6db1703fc6d2",
        "score": 0.6027405,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 9: Settlement and Billing of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025. It lists various sections related to payments and charges within the energy market. These include:\n\n- MRA (Market Resource Adequacy) payments and charges for capital expenditures, deployment events, variable payments, unexcused misconduct, and service charges.\n- Voltage support service payments and charges.\n- Black start services, including hourly standby fee and capacity charges.\n- Payments for emergency operations and real-time revenue neutrality allocation.\n- Emergency response service capacity payments and charges.\n- Firm fuel supply service payments, including hourly standby fee and capacity charges.\n- Real-time settlement for updated day-ahead market ancillary service obligations.\n- Regulation up and down service payments and charges.\n- Responsive reserve payments and charges.\n- Non-spinning reserve service payments and charges.\n- ERCOT contingency reserve service payments and charges.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_17.jpg",
          "page_num": 17,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e39a8580-984f-47c1-80aa-4509eba82827",
        "score": 0.60119,
        "text": "The document page is from Section 9: Settlement and Billing of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025. It outlines various sections related to real-time payments, charges, and deviations in the energy market. Key points include:\n\n- Real-time payments and charges for block load transfer points, high dispatch limits, and energy from specific generators and storage systems.\n- Congestion payments and charges for self-schedules.\n- Set point deviation charges for over and under generation, as well as for controllable load resources and energy storage resources.\n- RMR (Reliability Must-Run) payments, adjustments, charges for unexcused misconduct, and service charges.\n- Methods for reconciling RMR costs and expenses.\n- MRA (Market Resource Adequacy) standby payments.\n\nEach section specifies different aspects of settlement and billing related to energy generation, storage, and consumption.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_16.jpg",
          "page_num": 16,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7b43829e-8e02-438d-bc60-3f47bcbbe96e",
        "score": 0.59744245,
        "text": "The document outlines specific protocols related to settlement and billing within the ERCOT system. Key sections include:\n\n1. **Short Payments Handling (Section 9.19.3)**: Short payments of Default Uplift Invoices must be managed under Section 9.19, specifically addressing Partial Payments by Invoice Recipients.\n\n2. **Default Uplift Supporting Data Reporting (Section 9.19.3)**: ERCOT is required to post monthly data on the MIS Certified Area, including Maximum MWh Activity (MMA), Maximum MWh Activity Total (MMATOT), Maximum MWh Activity Ratio Share (MMARS), and Counter-Party level components. This data is updated with Final and True-Up Settlement data when available.\n\n3. **Exemption for Central Counter-Party Clearinghouses (Section 9.19.4)**: ERCOT will not issue Default Uplift Invoices to entities acting as central Counter-Party clearinghouses in wholesale market transactions if they are regulated as Derivatives Clearing Organizations under the Commodity Exchange Act.\n\n4. **ERCOT Invoice Report (Section 9.20)**: ERCOT will post daily reports on the Market Information System (MIS) listing various invoices issued to Qualified Scheduling Entities (QSEs) and Congestion Revenue Right (CRR) Account Holders. These include Settlement, CRR Auction, CRR Auction Revenue Distribution, CRR Balancing Account, and Miscellaneous Invoices. \n\nThis document is part of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols effective February 1, 2025.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_69.jpg",
          "page_num": 69,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
