          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0aad7629-e121-4089-80f9-9d8626b5d0e1",
        "score": 0.5945078,
        "text": "The document outlines the standard operation and maintenance (O&M) costs for various resource categories starting from 2009, with a focus on startup and variable O&M costs. Key points include:\n\n1. **Resource Categories and Costs**:\n   - Different categories such as gas-steam supercritical boiler, nuclear, coal, lignite, hydro, and renewables have specified costs for cold, intermediate, and hot startups, as well as variable O&M costs per MWh.\n   - Costs vary significantly between categories, with renewables having no applicable startup costs.\n\n2. **Cost Reduction**:\n   - From January 1, 2013, standard O&M costs are reduced by 20% from the specified levels.\n\n3. **Specific Costs for Aeroderivative and Reciprocating Engines**:\n   - Aeroderivative simple cycle engines have a flat startup cost of $800 and a variable O&M cost of $3.15/MWh.\n   - Reciprocating engines have costs based on the seasonal net max sustainable ratings, with a variable O&M cost of $4.07/MWh.\n\n4. **Combined Cycle Configurations**:\n   - Startup costs for combined-cycle configurations are calculated as the sum of the startup costs for each unit within the configuration.\n\n5. **Conditions for Using Standard O&M Costs**:\n   - If a QSE or Resource Entity opts for standard O&M costs, these will be used by ERCOT until verifiable variable O&M costs are filed or other conditions are met.\n\nThis document is part of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025, and focuses on transmission security analysis and reliability unit commitment.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_5:_Transmission_Security_Analysis_and_Reliability_Unit_Commitment/page_31.jpg",
          "page_num": 31,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 5: Transmission Security Analysis and Reliability Unit Commitment",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4dfc70f7-9ef8-4a64-b3a1-625343536d5f",
        "score": 0.59383273,
        "text": "The document is from Section 5 of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, focusing on Transmission Security Analysis and Reliability Unit Commitment. It outlines procedures for Qualified Scheduling Entities (QSEs) regarding the submission and updating of verifiable cost data for resources. Key points include:\n\n1. **Submission of Verifiable Costs**: QSEs can submit data from resources as verifiable costs at any time, and this data will be considered by ERCOT. A Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) is not required for this submission.\n\n2. **Notification for Updates**: ERCOT will notify a QSE to update verifiable cost data if a resource receives more than 50 RUC instructions in a year or if at least five years have passed since the last approval.\n\n3. **Submission Deadlines**: QSEs must submit updated verifiable cost data within 30 days of receiving a notice from ERCOT. Failure to do so will result in the use of generic cost caps until updated data is approved.\n\n4. **Exclusions**: Energy Storage Resources (ESRs) are excluded from submitting verifiable costs.\n\n5. **Verifiable Startup Costs**: Details the calculation of startup costs for resources, including fuel consumption rates and associated costs, as per the Verifiable Cost Manual.\n\nThis section ensures that ERCOT maintains accurate and up-to-date cost data for resource management and operational efficiency.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_5:_Transmission_Security_Analysis_and_Reliability_Unit_Commitment/page_33.jpg",
          "page_num": 33,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 5: Transmission Security Analysis and Reliability Unit Commitment",
