        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 16, which deals with the registration and qualification of market participants. It outlines parameters and procedures for determining financial risk and creditworthiness of Counter-Parties involved in the market.\n\n1. **Parameters Table**: \n   - **T5**: Days value for a Counter-Party representing Load is 5, otherwise 2.\n   - **BTCF**: Percentage set at 80%.\n   - **n**: Days set at 14.\n\n2. **Parameter Updates**: ERCOT will update these parameters monthly, following approval from the ERCOT Board, and will notify the market before implementing changes.\n\n3. **Financial Risk Assessment**:\n   - ERCOT can adjust the Total Potential Exposure Amount (TPEA) or Total Potential Exposure for Settlement (TPES) if the calculated values do not match the financial risk posed by a Counter-Party's activities.\n   - ERCOT will provide the Counter-Party with information and a written or electronic notice explaining the assessment and creditworthiness requirements.\n\n4. **Daily Monitoring**: ERCOT will monitor and calculate each Counter-Party\u2019s TPEA and TPES daily.\n\n5. **Initial Estimated Liability (IEL) Calculation**:\n   - For most Counter-Parties, ERCOT will determine an IEL for creditworthiness purposes.\n   - For Counter-Parties with all Qualified Scheduling Entities (QSEs) representing only Load Serving Entities (LSEs), the IEL is calculated using a specific formula: \n     \\[\n     \\text{IEL} = \\text{DEL} \\times \\max(0.2, \\text{RTFL}) \\times \\text{RTAEP} \\times (\\text{M1} + \\text{M2})\n     \\]\n   - **Variables**:\n     - **IEL**: Initial Estimated Liability.\n     - **DEL**: Daily Estimated Load in MWh.\n     - **RTFL**: Real-Time Energy Factor for Load.\n     - **RTAEP**: Real-Time Average Energy Price in $/MWh.\n\nThis section ensures that ERCOT can effectively manage and assess the financial risks associated with market participants.",
