        "text": "The document outlines the standard operation and maintenance (O&M) costs for various resource categories starting from 2009, with a focus on startup and variable O&M costs. Key points include:\n\n1. **Resource Categories and Costs**:\n   - Different categories such as gas-steam supercritical boiler, nuclear, coal, lignite, hydro, and renewables have specified costs for cold, intermediate, and hot startups, as well as variable O&M costs per MWh.\n   - Costs vary significantly between categories, with renewables having no applicable startup costs.\n\n2. **Cost Reduction**:\n   - From January 1, 2013, standard O&M costs are reduced by 20% from the specified levels.\n\n3. **Specific Costs for Aeroderivative and Reciprocating Engines**:\n   - Aeroderivative simple cycle engines have a flat startup cost of $800 and a variable O&M cost of $3.15/MWh.\n   - Reciprocating engines have costs based on the seasonal net max sustainable ratings, with a variable O&M cost of $4.07/MWh.\n\n4. **Combined Cycle Configurations**:\n   - Startup costs for combined-cycle configurations are calculated as the sum of the startup costs for each unit within the configuration.\n\n5. **Conditions for Using Standard O&M Costs**:\n   - If a QSE or Resource Entity opts for standard O&M costs, these will be used by ERCOT until verifiable variable O&M costs are filed or other conditions are met.\n\nThis document is part of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, dated February 1, 2025, and focuses on transmission security analysis and reliability unit commitment.",
